When we were growing up, discipline was a shared community responsibility and any villager could ‘punish you’ if they caught you misbehaving.
Corporal punishment
However, things have changed drastically and child rights activism has stolen the thunder from parenting. Children dictate terms and parents have to oblige. This liberalism has contributed to rising cases of indiscipline in our learning institutions, largely because some students want to enjoy the same freedom and leeway they get at home back in school.
 In fact, the abolishment of corporal punishment in schools has added to the challenges facing teachers as they struggle to correct bad behaviour that children import to school due to poor parenting.
On the one hand, imparting discipline in learners should be viewed as a multipronged issue, where several approaches should be applied depending on the nature of the cases at hand.



